    <prj:ScienceGoal mode="Standard">
        <prj:name>Massive filaments as bundles of fibers</prj:name>
        <prj:note>The study of the B213 filament in Taurus have demonstrated the key role of fibers as the fundamental building blocks of more complex filaments. This level of substructure radically changes our interpretation of internal gas evolution inside objects like B213: If considered simple and monolithic form the analysis of its continuum emission, the B213 filament would result into a highly unstable filament, most likely collapsing into a spindle in timescales comparable free-fall time without fragmenting (e.g. see Inutsuka &amp; Miyama 1992); Contrary to this interpretation, the presence of these bundles of fibers naturally explains the large scale stability of B213 while allow its fragmentation and collapse in only those regions where the gas became locally unstable.

With this Science Goal #1 we aim to investigate whether these fibers and their association in bundles can also explain the internal substructure and stability of more massive filaments like the ISF in Orion. To address this question we plan to obtain a large 148-pointings mosaic of the OMC-2 region using the N2H+(1-0) emission as a tracer of its internal mass distribution. The presence of fibers in this regions could potentially unify our understanding of the internal evolution of both low- and high-mass filaments in molecular clouds.
</prj:note>
