        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our detailed analysis of the gas kinematics inside the the ISF using our FIVe algorithm requires a full description of the line emission profiles. According to our IRAM30m data, along the ISF the typical N2H+ (1-0) line FWHMs are estimated on &gt; 0.5 kms-1. In Dual polarization mode and at the frequencies of the NH2+ emission (93.173 GHz), the maximum spectral resolution available is 0.098 kms-1 (or 39 kHz). With this spectral resolution we then expect to resolve the observed N2H+ lines with at least 5 channels per line as a essential requirement for our study.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The main goal of this proposal is to recover the internal substructure of the ISF filament down to scales of 0.01 pc (or 3.7 arcsec). The maximum angular resolution achieved in this project would allow us to resolve fiber-like structures similar to those already recovered in OMC-4, with sizes of ~0.2-0.3 pc, with &gt;30 pixel elements. 

To achive this goal, we request the use of ALMA in the C36-1 array configuration. According to the ALMA Observing Tool, the largest angular scale recovered in this configuration is 26.5 arcsec. This angular resolution matches the beam size of our N2H+ IRAM30m observations. By the combination of these two datasets, we would be then able to recover all the flux at the relevant scales for this project. 

As important remark, our high-sensitivity IRAM30m data present rms values of ~0.15 K. This sensitivity level is a factor of ~2 better than the expected final sensitivity our the proposed ALMA mosaics. 

The use of our Nyquist-sample and high-sensitivity IRAM30m data allow us to save the ACA observations (i.e. ~6 hours of additional observations for the total mosaic), otherwise necessary to recover the extended emission in the ISF.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our analysis of the gas kinematics traced by the N2H+ emission is based on a full description of the line profiles using hyperfine line fits. To carry out this analysis, an homogeneous SNR &gt; 3 is requiered for the entire mosaic proposed in this Science Goal. We measure typical peak line temperatures of T &gt; 1 K at the resolution of our single-dish IRAM30m maps for the N2H+(1-0) lines along the whole ISF. As a conservative approach, we assume this N2H+ emission with a filling factor of 1 at the resolution of our single-dish data (26.5 arcsec). Out single-dish measurements would then lead into a similar T&gt;1K for the expected line intensities at the final ALMA mosaic with a resolution of 3.7 arcsec. The proposed rms goal of 0.25 K would then guaranteed the requiered signal-to-noise values of SNR&gt;3.

Three spectral windows would be observed as part of this project. The first one, and as the science target of this proposal, corresponds to the high-spectral resolution (59MHz), narrow (31KHz) windown centered at the frequency of the N2H+ (1-0) line at 93.173 GHz. This requested fine spectral resolution (0.098 km-s1) is necessary to resolve in velocities the narrow lines detected in our single-dish IRAM30m observations (FWHM ~ 0.5 kms-1). Two secondary broad spectral windows, with a total bandwidths of 1.8 GHz each, would be observed in parallel for calibration porpuses.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
