    <prj:ScienceGoal mode="Standard">
        <prj:name>Comparing the kinematic properties of fibers in different environments</prj:name>
        <prj:note>While fibers could explain the internal substructure of massive filaments like the ISF, it is still unclear whether their properties remain universal. Are their internal properties (kinematics, sizes, linear massses, densities...) environmentally dependent? could the variation of these properties explain the different star-formation regimes observe in different clouds?

To address this question with this Science Goal #2 we plan to compare the results obtained in OMC-2 with a similar 148-pointings mosaic of the OMC-1 region also in N2H+(1-0). From the analysis in these two regions, and in combination with our previous results in OMC-4, we aim to obtain a statistically significant census of the fibers within the ISF. By comparing these 3 SF-regions, and in addition to our Taurus results, we will explore the variations on the fiber properties in different conditions across several orders of magnitud in density from the diffuse, low-mass B213 filament to the most compact and denser environments like OMC-1. </prj:note>
