        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our analysis of the gas kinematics traced by the N2H+ emission is based on a full description of the line profiles using hyperfne line fits. To carry out these analysis, an homogeneous SNR &gt; 3 is requiered for the entire mosaic proposed in this Science Goal. We measure typical peak line temperatures of T &gt; 1K at the resolution of our single-dish IRAM30m maps for the N2H+(1-0) lines along the whole ISF. As a conservative approach, we assume this N2H+ emission with a filling factor of 1 at the resolution of our single-dish data (26.5 arcsec). Our single-dish measurements would then lead into similar T &gt; 1K for the line intensities expected at the final resolution of this new ALMA observations (3.7 arcsec). The proposed rms goal of 0.25 K would then guarranteed the reuiered signal-to-noise value of SNR &gt;3.

Three spectral windows would be observed as part of this project. The first one, and as the science target of this proposal, corresponds to the high-spectral resolution (59MHz), narrow (31KHz) windown centered at the frequency of the N2H+ (1-0) line at 93.173 GHz. This requested fine spectral resolution (0.098 km-s1) is necessary to resolve in velocities the narrow lines detected in our single-dish IRAM30m observations (FWHM ~ 0.5 kms-1). Two secondary broad spectral windows, with a total bandwidths of 1.8 GHz each, would be observed in parallel for calibration porpuses.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
